inlineContent.text: When the date returned by the
method of your data source passes, ClockKit begins a scheduled update of your complication. At the start of that update, it calls this method or the

method to let you know that the requested update has begun. These methods are your opportunity to tell ClockKit whether or not you’ve new data to add to your timeline. When this method is called, it’s your last opportunity to update your timeline until its budget is replenished.
If you’ve new data for your timeline, your implementation of this method should call the

method of the complication server. ClockKit doesn’t ask your data source for new timeline entries unless you call one of those methods. If you do nothing or don’t implement this method, ClockKit calls only the
of your data source to fetch a new update time.

abstract.text: Display app-specific data on the clock face.

Returns the list of complication descriptors.
Retrieves the timeline entry that you want to display now.
Gets a localizable template that shows sample data for the specified complication.

Returns the privacy behavior for the specified complication.
Determines whether your complication can provide timeline entries for the future or the past.
Gets the animation behavior when transitioning between timeline entries.

Informs the app about complications from a shared watch face.
